“Trying” is the flagship single from Bully’s debut album, Feels Like.

Alicia tackles the issues of her own self-restraint and judgment in this song. Each of the verses expresses various focal points for her self-criticism. In the chorus, she reflects on how she’s trying to ease up, but will probably always continue to be hypercritical of herself and her actions.

On August 18th, 2015, Bully played this song live on CONAN, as seen here:

body.plain:
“Trying” is the flagship single from Bully’s debut album, Feels Like.

Alicia tackles the issues of her own self-restraint and judgment in this song. Each of the verses expresses various focal points for her self-criticism. In the chorus, she reflects on how she’s trying to ease up, but will probably always continue to be hypercritical of herself and her actions.

annotations: Been praying for my period all week
Her period is late, and she is starting to get worried that she might be pregnant which is not ideal.

I’m trying, I am
 I’m trying, I am
 Trying to hide from my mind, I am
 Trying all the time, I am
 Trying to hide from my mind, I am
 Trying, trying
 Why am I?
Alicia’s saying that she is attempting to keep herself together and “shield” herself from her internal battles.

If it counts for anything
 I didn’t want to
 I’m just looking for clarity
 To help me get through

These lines are an admittance of awareness to Bognanno’s own faults. She never wanted to “hide from [her] mind,” but ended up doing so to protect herself. Now she’s looking to escape the entrapment of her self-imposed restriction in order to form a clearer picture of herself.
There’s no flawless education, just a stupid degree

She has beef with the education system. Growing up, we’re taught that all we need to be successful is a good education. Alicia echoes the sentiment that many people have: what good is devoting yourself to your education, if all you get from it is a piece of paper?

annotations:
I could be a milkman
 Or I could get up and I could be what I want to be

Back in their heyday, milkmen were necessary, since a lack of widespread quality cold storage meant milk and other dairy products quickly spoiled. However, since the popularization of the in-home refrigerator, milkmen have become obsolete.

Alicia equates the pointless nature of being a milkman in today’s society with the version of herself she could become if she fails to follow her dreams.

I used to be a shark
 I used to be a shark
 I used to be a shark
 Oh I used to be a....
 SHARK! SHARK! SHARK!

Much like a shark is considered to be one of the fiercest predators in the oceans, she was once a fiercely confident and effective when interacting with the people she cared about. Now she feels like she has lost that ability, and calls out to the strength she used to have.
But I’m just a circle in Logan’s square

Logan Square is a community area in the city of Chicago.

Though she was born in Minnesota, Bognanno has love for Chicago, as she professes in this interview. By referencing Logan Square, she is paying homage to Chicago and identifying with what she feels it represents.



This line uses conceptual wordplay, drawing from the idiom, “You can’t fit a square peg in a round hole,” but reversing the roles so the peg is circular (Alicia), and the hole is a square (Logan Square). A circular peg can fit in a square hole, but it doesn’t fill it – there is still space in the corners. Similarly, Alicia loves Chicago and enjoys visiting, but doesn’t quite feel like it’s where she belongs.

annotations: I know when you mean it

In relation to the prior line this could be interpreted to be Alicia’s way of saying that she knows when he is truly sad versus where it is act.

The line also works standalone way of saying that she can tell when he is telling the truth and when he is lying. Their closeness and time they’ve spent together puts her in a position such that she can read him completely.
I know what makes you cry

This line refers to the fact that she knows the things that affect him deepest, the things that a person only shares with the person closest to them.

In the context of the other lines “I remember hurting you do bad” and knowing what makes him “mad” and “melt”, this line could also refer to intentional (or unintentional) manipulations from her: She knows what to say and do to hurt him.

Who knows you better than
 I do!
She is proclaiming to know her ex-boyfriend better than anyone else as a result of their very close prior (and arguably still existing) connection.

body.plain: This song seems to be Alicia rebelling against “every tradition” expected by women in modern-day society; specifically (the second verse) having children and (the third verse) getting married.

annotations:
I never put the blame on you
 I never put the blame on you
 I never put the blame on you

They never blamed their partner for wanting a traditional life, nor did they blame them for the relationship ending. The bittersweetness of a relationship ending like this is that there is no blame to be found, no fault to follow, no fingers to point. This is simply the tragic tale of two people who love each other wanting drastically different things from this life.

It’s evocative, you’re so convincing
 Yeah, I hear you, but nothing’s changed for me
 Nothing’s changed for me

Although the subject makes a good argument for the joys that can be found by following a traditional lifestyle, the subject remains firm in their resistance to such a life. They understand the advantages to sticking to tradition but it simply is not what they want from life.
Wasting my time, second-guessing what I need
They narrator has wasted so much of their time doubting and neglecting their own wants and needs as they’ve attempted to acquiesce to the subject’s life plans and societal expectations.

Don’t need you to save me
 Something’s off, you’re wrong about the dream

The narrator doesn’t need someone to convince them that not wanting to have a traditional life is bad and argues that the subject is wrong about marriage and children being the only path to a happy and fulfilled life.

If you’re gonna shame me
 Turn around, bite your tongue ’til it bleeds

Women are often faced with societal pressure that restricts them within narrow confines of what a good woman should be and do. Traditionally, this involves assuming the role of wife and mother, both of which the narrator rejects. More commonly than ever, women today have more freedom to reject these societal expectations, however, they are still often stigmatised for these decisions. The narrator thus announces that if the subject wishes to make her a victim of this judgment, they should hold back whatever opinions they have about how she lives her own life.

If you’re gonna shame me
 Turn around, bite your tongue ’til it bleeds

Women are often faced with societal pressure that restricts them within narrow confines of what a good woman should be and do. Traditionally, this involves assuming the role of wife and mother, both of which the narrator rejects. More commonly than ever, women today have more freedom to reject these societal expectations, however, they are still often stigmatised for these decisions. The narrator thus announces that if the subject wishes to make her a victim of this judgment, they should hold back whatever opinions they have about how she lives her own life.

You say my mind is gonna change one day
 But I felt this way forever
 Some things stay the same
 I stay the same

The narrator has never wanted a traditional lifestyle and has been transparent about this decision seemingly since the beginning of their relationship, yet the subject hoped that their mind would change eventually (and maybe still thinks it will). This appears to have always been a rift in the relationship, but the narrator is finally making it abundantly clear that their stance on the matter is unmoving. As the saying goes, some things never change.

Forgetting all that comes with space
 Like your hello I still retrace

The narrator has been in a relationship with the subject long enough to forget what it’s like to be separated from them. They still find themself falling into old habits of seeking out the comfort of their past love.

And I think unknowing you
 Is the hardest thing I ever had to do

The relationship ended not because they stopped loving and caring for each other, but because the hopes for their future lifestyles were incompatible. Breakups like these where neither party did anything ‘wrong’ can be the hardest because there is no anger or frustration to dull the hurt. Moving on from an ex is hard enough, but forcing yourself to fall out of love with someone who did nothing wrong and who you still care deeply about feels nearly impossible.

You beat yourself up wondering why I won’t take a vow
 I don’t even wanna try

The subject blames themselves for the narrators refusal to get married which contributes to the unhealthy dynamic in their relationship. This song is thus a melodic extension of the phrase “it’s not you, it’s me”. The narrator assures the subject that their refusal to marry is not through any fault of the subject, but simply because the narrator does not wish to follow a traditional’ lifestyle. Although they care about the subject, the narrator is aware that they cannot be the person they need and want from a relationship.
